{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501838"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:34:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:34:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1797"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1797","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1797"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.55,0.1,0.06,0.27,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1797"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78386"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1797","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1797"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1797"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63748"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"461"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1151"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1948"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7649"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43853"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44777"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78386"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of progressive difficulty swallowing. He can now only manage liquids and soft foods. He denies weight loss, regurgitation, pain on swallowing, heartburn or breathlessness. He has a 20-year history of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease treated with pantoprazole. He does not take any other regular medications. His medical history is otherwise unremarkable. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history and drinks three standard alcoholic drinks daily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His body mass index is 35 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. He has a husky voice and a non-tender 2 cm mass in the left supraclavicular fossa. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate diagnostic investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Endoscopy","Barium swallow","Chest X-ray","Computed tomography of chest and abdomen","Indirect laryngoscopy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suspicious for oesophageal cancer, including progressive dysphagia, risk factors (chronic reflux, smoking), and an enlarged Virchow\u0027s node suggesting metastatic spread. The husky voice may indicate recurrent laryngeal nerve involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial investigation as it allows direct visualisation of the oesophageal mucosa and, crucially, enables tissue biopsy for definitive diagnosis. It can also assess the extent of the lesion and identify other pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBarium swallow\u003C/strong\u003E can demonstrate oesophageal narrowing or filling defects but cannot provide tissue diagnosis. While it may be useful in some cases, it is not the first-line investigation when cancer is suspected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E has limited utility in evaluating dysphagia. While it may show mediastinal widening or lung metastases, it cannot diagnose oesophageal pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography\u003C/strong\u003E of chest and abdomen is essential for staging once the diagnosis is confirmed but is not the most appropriate initial diagnostic test. It provides information about local invasion and distant spread but cannot reliably confirm the diagnosis without tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIndirect laryngoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E examines the larynx and hypopharynx but cannot evaluate the oesophagus. While it may be useful later to assess for vocal cord paralysis, it is not appropriate as the initial diagnostic test for suspected oesophageal cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Endoscopy is the first-line investigation for suspected oesophageal cancer as it allows direct visualisation and biopsy","Progressive dysphagia, particularly in the context of risk factors like chronic GORD and smoking, should raise suspicion for oesophageal cancer","A left supraclavicular lymph node (Virchow\u0027s node) suggests metastatic disease"],"references":["Gibbs JF, Rajput A, Chadha KS, Douglas WG, Hill H, Nwogu C, Nava HR, Sabel MS. The changing profile of esophageal cancer presentation and its implication for diagnosis. J Natl Med Assoc. 2007 Jun;99(6):620-6. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2574377/","Recio-Boiles A, Babiker HM. Esophageal Cancer. In: StatPearls [Online]. [Updated 2020 Nov 19]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459267/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63748"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1797"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63748","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63748"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T14:27:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-10T14:27:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data"